review_blob:
Pours a dark black with nice dark tan head that sticks around for the long haul.  Slight roasted aroma.  Nice hop / malt balance.  

---Rated via Beer Buddy

Not a huge bourbon fan, but I do like this beer!  Nice dark pour with a dark tan head.  Aroma up front was straight bourbon.  After it warmed a bit you get the roasted aromas as well.  The taste has that chocolatey bitterness and roasty flavor, but it still has that sweetness and warmth from the bourbon.  

---Rated via Beer Buddy
beer_name: Laughing Dog The Dogfather Imperial Stout

review_blob:
Tsjeeses Reserva, bottle from 2010 I believe.  Pours almost a pinkish amber, 1-finger head which disappears quickly.  Aroma has tons of fruit ( cherries, plum, grapes), Christmas spices, and candy.  Very easy drinking and quite potent.  I make it a point to get a bottle of this brew every year for New Years Day!

---Rated via Beer Buddy

Pours an orangey gold with a bubbley head that dissappears in time.  Funky, lemony, apples, in the aroma.  Aggressive carbonation that enhances the tart/funk, but is balanced by an underlying sweetness in the tongue.

---Rated via Beer Buddy
beer_name: Sierra Nevada / Russian River BRUX Domesticated Wild Ale

review_blob:
750 bottle.  Nice head which left a nice lacing on the glass.  A strong piney, slight grapefruit aroma.  Crisp, hoppy, and balanced.  Only got the hint of sweetness once this beer warmed up a bit.  A nice drinkable IPA.

---Rated via Beer Buddy

Dark brown, light tan head dissapates quickly.  Nicely Roasted and spiced aroma.  Should have let it warm up before tasting as the roasted flavor was a bit washed out due to cold temps.

---Rated via Beer Buddy
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2001 and earlier)

review_blob: Bottle 7.8%abv.  Pours a rich, deep, dark, amber with an oatmeal colored 1/2 finger head, which quickly dissapeared.  It smelled Raisiny, slightly Roasty, but mostly of malty sweetness.  It tastes malty sweet up front with more slight hints of raisin, you get a tiny bit of alchohol up the nose at this time, but all this passes and turns into a deep roasted dark chocolate bitterness at the back of the tongue.  I heard the brewer describe this beer as their Scotch Porter, and I couldnt describe it any better myself.  This beer is on the thicker side of the palate range, but not as heavy as say a Breakfast Stout.

Bottle. Pours a slightly cloudy Golden Amber with about 3/4 of a finger worth of white head.  Piney Hops aroma at first, which fades into a more floral hop aroma as the head dissappates.  Carbonated Hoppy bitter flavor up front, followed by a mild but noticeable floral hop flavor, with a balanced hoppy bitter finish.  Bitterness fades away and leaves you with a nice floral taste that lingers till your next sip.  I feel that this is a well balanced IPA, not too much or too little of any one thing.  Very drinkable.

Bottle.  Pours a thick black liquid with a dark tan, thin head.  Smells of malt, coffee, and chocolatey goodness.  Upfront taste of sweet coffee, with a great bitter dark, dark chocolate aftertaste.  One sip coats every surface of the mouth for a long and lasting taste experience.  The thin head dissapeared shortly after pouring, but a decent lacing coats the glass for a while after each sip.  So wrapped up in the taste experience, the alchohol goes unnoticed until its thoroughly done its job.

Bottle.  pours a golden color.  Small lasting head. Very citrusy aroma, screaming grapefruit and lemons and hints of pine, not so much of the floral for me.  Was sweet (bordering on too sweet at times) on the tongue. But balanced by a nice bitter aftertaste.  Didnt notice the alchohol till afterwards...
